Wall Street's Terren Peizer is like Woody Allen's Zelig: he shows up in some of the oddest places.A decade ago, Mr. Peizer was Michael R. Milken's left-hand man, and later a star witness against Mr. Milken at his sentencing for securities fraud. In the mid-90's, Mr. Peizer played a small role in the convoluted drama surrounding Towers Financial, the debt-collection-agency-cum-pyramid-scheme founded by Steven Hoffenberg. And he was an investor in several small companies.Now Mr. Peizer has turned up as the president of Hollis-Eden Pharmaceuticals Inc., a fledgling drug company with a stock that has soared 170 percent this year, to $16.75 on Friday. While biotechnology stocks have been making something of a comeback lately, the Nasdaq index of these shares, which includes Hollis-Eden, has risen just 5.7 percent this year.While Hollis-Eden's market value, $112 million, might seem big for a company with no sales, much less earnings, Mr. Peizer is passionate about the prospects for its anti-AIDS drugs, and he is a persuasive salesman. ''This is a once in a lifetime opportunity for me,'' he said last week. ''We have something special.''If he is right, ultimately nothing else about Hollis-Eden will matter much. But similar hopes are shared by the investors in many of the hundreds of little biotechnology companies out there, not all of which are quite as quirky as Hollis-Eden -- and only a few of which will probably hit the big time.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Unlike many biotechnology companies, Hollis-Eden has not been vetted by a big brokerage firm that wants to take it public or a big pharmaceutical company that wants to be its partner (though Mr. Peizer hints of a partnership deal ahead). Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





The company was founded in 1994 by Richard B. Hollis, who had worked for several medical companies, and Patrick T. Prendergast, an Irish scientist. Dr. Prendergast had previously financed his research by treating race horses, Mr. Hollis said, adding that he had focused on a ''commercial perspective rather than an academic one, patents awards versus publishing papers.''In its first year and a half in business, Hollis-Eden devoted itself to trying to raise money, according to statements it filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission. In November 1996 it found a big source of $6 million in cash: the Initial Acquisition Corporation, which had gone public in 1995 as a blind pool, Wall Street's shorthand for ''give us the money now, and we'll buy a company to be named later.'' The underwriter was H. J. Meyers, which has a history of regulatory problems.A year ago, Mr. Peizer joined Hollis-Eden. Mr. Peizer, who had at first been interested in investing in the company, spent months checking it out, he said. Meanwhile, the company was looking into Mr. Peizer.''Obviously, someone with as high a profile as Terren, we had to do the same thing,'' Mr. Hollis said. He was comforted by the fact that Mr. Peizer had never been sanctioned by the Securities and Exchange Commission, he said, adding, ''I became very, very comfortable, and very confident in Terren's ability as a businessman and financier.''Mr. Peizer developed his high profile in his 20's, when he became a salesman at the Beverly Hills office of Drexel Burnham Lambert, where he sat next to the man he describes as the Babe Ruth of the bond business. Though he worked with and admired Mr. Milken, he said, he felt compelled to testify against his old boss when he discovered that improper things had been going on, ''and I wouldn't perjure myself, I wouldn't obstruct justice and I wouldn't destroy documents.''
