Afterward, Mr. Peizer became a private investor in small companies. He says he has made money in almost all of the roughly 30 companies in which he has invested. Some, like the shoe company now called Candies', are making money; others, like Urethane Technologies, a tire company, have gone bust. ''I shouldn't have left the board,'' he said of Urethane. ''They ran it into the ground.''In 1995, Mr. Peizer had another unpleasant brush with publicity when he was named in a lawsuit filed against John Hall, the man who was supposed to rebuild the remains of Towers Financial, renamed Qualis Care. Instead, Mr. Hall looted the company; he later pleaded guilty to fraud charges.Qualis's creditors complained that the company's money was used to repay a $5 million personal loan Mr. Peizer made to Mr. Hall, who used an additional $5 million of company money to buy stock from Mr. Peizer. Mr. Peizer has asked the court to dismiss the lawsuit against him, saying that he had nothing to do with Mr. Hall's improper activities.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

All of these experiences, Mr. Peizer said, have made him leery of ''the limelight, the sour light, the lemon light.'' But he was willing to take the rather public role at Hollis-Eden, he said, because he believed so strongly in the company's drugs.In a press release the company issued last week, it described three ''technology platforms'' it was working on, including a drug called Inactivin, or PPB2, which it said kept viruses from replicating using a different mechanism than current AIDS treatments. The company hopes to begin overseas clinical trials on this drug by the end of March, and to start such tests in the United States before the end of the year.Even so, the company is probably ''a number of years away'' from applying for approval from the Food and Drug Administration, said Dr. Thomas C. Merigan, a prominent AIDS researcher at Stanford University who is on the company's board  and is serving as a consultant to help it set up its clinical trials.As for the run-up in the stock price, he said, ''I don't understand the ways this happens.''Company officials say they are not behind the rise; despite the press release, they have been trying to keep a low profile, they say, and they do not think a brokerage firm is pushing the stock. Indeed, no analysts now cover the company, which plans to hold a ''road show'' for stockbrokers in New York this week.Mr. Hollis and Mr. Peizer suggested that the current boom in trading might have occurred because, in December, early investors who owned millions of shares became free to sell them. But Mr. Peizer and Mr. Hollis own almost half of the company's shares -- Mr. Peizer's first block of stock options just vested -- and say they have not sold any.Nor do they intend to, Mr. Peizer said. ''I would throw myself on the tracks,'' he said, ''if it would help this company.'' Continue reading the main story






